# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: unintentional-radiator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The earliest experimental AM transmissions began in the early 1900s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, widespread AM broadcasting was not established until the 1920s, following the development of vacuum tube receivers and transmitters.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] AM radio remained the dominant method of broadcasting for the next 30 years, a period called the "Golden Age of Radio", until television broadcasting became widespread in the 1950s and received much of the programming previously carried by radio.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Later, AM radio's audiences declined greatly due to competition from FM radio, digital radio, satellite radio, Internet radio, music streaming services, and podcasting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Thus, AM broadcasters tend to specialize in spoken-word formats, such as talk radio, all-news radio and sports radio, with music formats primarily for FM and digital stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] — Red Barber, *The Broadcasters*, 1970, pp.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In October 1898, a London publication, *The Electrician*, noted that "there are rare cases where, as Dr. [Oliver] Lodge once expressed it, it might be advantageous to 'shout' the message, spreading it broadcast to receivers in all directions".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, it was recognized that this would involve significant financial issues, as that same year *The Electrician* also commented "did not Prof.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] On January 1, 1902, Nathan Stubblefield gave a short-range "wireless telephone" demonstration, that included simultaneously broadcasting speech and music to seven locations throughout Murray, Kentucky.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The earliest public radiotelegraph broadcasts were provided as government services, beginning with daily time signals inaugurated on January 1, 1905, by a number of U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In Europe, signals transmitted from a station located on the Eiffel Tower were received throughout much of Europe.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In both the United States and France this led to a small market of receiver lines geared for jewelers who needed accurate time to set their clocks, including the Ondophone in France, and the De Forest RS-100 Jewelers Time Receiver in the United States.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The ability to pick up time signal broadcasts, in addition to Morse code weather reports and news summaries, also attracted the interest of amateur radio enthusiasts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] It was immediately recognized that, much like the telegraph had preceded the invention of the telephone, the ability to make audio radio transmissions would be a significant technical advance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Despite this knowledge, it still took two decades to perfect the technology needed to make quality audio transmissions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In addition, the telephone had rarely been used for distributing entertainment, outside of a few "telephone newspaper" systems, most of which were established in Europe, beginning with the Paris Théâtrophone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] With this in mind, most early radiotelephone development envisioned that the device would be more profitably developed as a "wireless telephone" for personal communication, or for providing links where regular telephone lines could not be run, rather than for the uncertain finances of broadcasting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The person generally credited as the primary early developer of AM technology is Canadian-born inventor Reginald Fessenden.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The original spark-gap radio transmitters were impractical for transmitting audio, since they produced discontinuous pulses known as "damped waves".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Fessenden realized that what was needed was a new type of radio transmitter that produced steady "undamped" (better known as "continuous wave") signals, which could then be "modulated" to reflect the sounds being transmitted.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Fessenden's basic approach was disclosed in U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Patent 706,737, which he applied for on May 29, 1901, and was issued the next year.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] It called for the use of a high-speed alternator (referred to as "an alternating-current dynamo") that generated "pure sine waves" and produced "a continuous train of radiant waves of substantially uniform strength", or, in modern terminology, a continuous-wave (CW) transmitter.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Fessenden began his research on audio transmissions while doing developmental work for the United States Weather Service on Cobb Island, Maryland.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Because he did not yet have a continuous-wave transmitter, initially he worked with an experimental "high-frequency spark" transmitter, taking advantage of the fact that the higher the spark rate, the closer a spark-gap transmission comes to producing continuous waves.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] He later reported that, in the fall of 1900, he successfully transmitted speech over a distance of about 1.6 kilometers (one mile), which appears to have been the first successful audio transmission using radio signals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, at this time the sound was far too distorted to be commercially practical.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] For a time he continued working with more sophisticated high-frequency spark transmitters, including versions that used compressed air, which began to take on some of the characteristics of arc-transmitters.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Fessenden attempted to sell this form of radiotelephone for point-to-point communication, but was unsuccessful.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Fessenden's work with high-frequency spark transmissions was only a temporary measure.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The next step, adopted from standard wire-telephone practice, was to insert a simple carbon microphone into the transmission line, to modulate the carrier wave signal to produce AM audio transmissions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, it would take many years of expensive development before even a prototype alternator-transmitter would be ready, and a few years beyond that for high-power versions to become available.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Fessenden worked with General Electric's (GE) Ernst F.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Alexanderson, who in August 1906, delivered an improved model which operated at a transmitting frequency of approximately 50 kHz, although at low power.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The alternator-transmitter achieved the goal of transmitting quality audio signals, but the lack of any way to amplify the signals meant they were somewhat weak.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] On December 21, 1906, Fessenden made an extensive demonstration of the new alternator-transmitter at Brant Rock, Massachusetts, showing its utility for point-to-point wireless telephony, including interconnecting his stations to the wire telephone network.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] As part of the demonstration, speech was transmitted 18 kilometers (11 miles) to a listening site at Plymouth, Massachusetts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Because there was no way to amplify electrical currents at this time, modulation was usually accomplished by a carbon microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] This meant that the full transmitter power flowed through the microphone, and even using water cooling, the power handling ability of the microphones severely limited the power of the transmissions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Ultimately only a small number of large and powerful Alexanderson alternators would be developed.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, they would be almost exclusively used for long-range radiotelegraph communication, and occasionally for radiotelephone experimentation, but were never used for general broadcasting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Almost all of the continuous wave AM transmissions made prior to 1915 were made by versions of the arc converter transmitter, which had been initially developed by Valdemar Poulsen in 1903.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Arc transmitters worked by producing a pulsating electrical arc in an enclosed hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] They were much more compact than alternator transmitters, and could operate on somewhat higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, they suffered from some of the same deficiencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The lack of any means to amplify electrical currents meant that, like the alternator transmitters, modulation was usually accomplished by a microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire, which again resulted in overheating issues, even with the use of water-cooled microphones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Thus, transmitter powers tended to be limited.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The arc was also somewhat unstable, which reduced audio quality.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Experimenters who used arc transmitters for their radiotelephone research included Ernst Ruhmer, Quirino Majorana, Charles "Doc" Herrold, and Lee de Forest.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Advances in vacuum tube technology (called "valves" in British usage), especially after around 1915, revolutionized radio technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tube devices could be used to amplify electrical currents, which overcame the overheating issues of needing to insert microphones directly in the transmission antenna circuit.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tube transmitters also provided high-quality AM signals, and could operate on higher transmitting frequencies than alternator and arc transmitters.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tubes remained the central technology of radio for 40 years, until transistors began to dominate in the late 1950s, and are still used in the highest power broadcast transmitters.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Unlike telegraph and telephone systems, which used completely different types of equipment, most radio receivers were equally suitable for both radiotelegraph and radiotelephone reception.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1903 and 1904, the electrolytic detector and thermionic diode (Fleming valve) were invented by Reginald Fessenden and John Ambrose Fleming, respectively.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Most important, in 1904–1906, the crystal detector, the simplest and cheapest AM detector, was developed by G.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Homemade crystal radios spread rapidly during the next 15 years, providing ready audiences for the first radio broadcasts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] One limitation of crystals sets was the lack of amplifying the signals, so listeners had to use earphones, and it required the development of vacuum-tube receivers before loudspeakers could be used.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The dynamic cone loudspeaker, invented in 1924, greatly improved audio frequency response over the previous horn speakers, allowing music to be reproduced with good fidelity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] AM radio offered the highest sound quality available in a home audio device prior to the introduction of the high-fidelity, long-playing record in the late 1940s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Listening habits changed in the 1960s due to the introduction of the revolutionary transistor radio (Regency TR-1, the first transistor radio released December 1954), which was made possible by the invention of the transistor in 1948.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] (The transistor was invented at Bell labs and released in June 1948.) Their compact size — small enough to fit in a shirt pocket — and lower power requirements, compared to vacuum tubes, meant that for the first time radio receivers were readily portable.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The transistor radio became the most widely used communication device in history, with billions manufactured by the 1970s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Radio became a ubiquitous "companion medium" which people could take with them anywhere they went.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The demarcation between what is considered "experimental" and "organized" broadcasting is largely arbitrary.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Following World War I, the number of stations providing a regular broadcasting service greatly increased, primarily due to advances in vacuum-tube technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, there were numerous cases of entertainment broadcasts being presented on a regular schedule before their formal recognition by government regulators.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Because most longwave radio frequencies were used for international radiotelegraph communication, a majority of early broadcasting stations operated on mediumwave frequencies, whose limited range generally restricted them to local audiences.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] One method for overcoming this limitation, as well as a method for sharing program costs, was to create radio networks, linking stations together with telephone lines to provide a nationwide audience.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In the U.S., the American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T) was the first organization to create a radio network, and also to promote commercial advertising, which it called "toll" broadcasting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Its flagship station, WEAF (now WFAN) in New York City, sold blocks of airtime to commercial sponsors that developed entertainment shows containing commercial messages.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] AT&T held a monopoly on quality telephone lines, and by 1924 had linked 12 stations in Eastern cities into a "chain".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The Radio Corporation of America (RCA), General Electric, and Westinghouse organized a competing network around its own flagship station, RCA's WJZ (now WABC) in New York City, but were hampered by AT&T's refusal to lease connecting lines or allow them to sell airtime.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1926, AT&T sold its radio operations to RCA, which used them to form the nucleus of the new NBC network.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] By the 1930s, most of the major radio stations in the country were affiliated with networks owned by two companies, NBC and CBS.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1934, a third national network, the Mutual Radio Network, was formed as a cooperative owned by its stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] A second country which quickly adopted network programming was the United Kingdom, and its national network quickly became a prototype for a state-managed monopoly of broadcasting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] A rising interest in radio broadcasting by the British public pressured the government to reintroduce the service, following its suspension in 1920.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, the government also wanted to avoid what it termed the "chaotic" U.S. experience of allowing large numbers of stations to operate with few restrictions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] There were also concerns about broadcasting becoming dominated by the Marconi company.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Arrangements were made for six large radio manufacturers to form a consortium, the British Broadcasting Company (BBC), established on October 18, 1922, which was given a monopoly on broadcasting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] This enterprise was supported by a tax on radio sets sales, plus an annual license fee on receivers, collected by the Post Office.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Initially the eight stations were allowed regional autonomy.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1927, the original broadcasting organization was replaced by a government chartered British Broadcasting Corporation. an independent nonprofit supported solely by a 10 shilling receiver license fee.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Both highbrow and mass-appeal programs were carried by the National and Regional networks.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The period from the early 1920s through the 1940s is often called the "Golden Age of Radio".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] During this period AM radio was the main source of home entertainment, until it was replaced by television.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] For the first time entertainment was provided from outside the home, replacing traditional forms of entertainment such as oral storytelling and music from family members.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] New forms were created, including radio plays, mystery serials, soap operas, quiz shows, variety hours, situation comedies and children's shows.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Radio news, including remote reporting, allowed listeners to be vicariously present at notable events.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Radio greatly eased the isolation of rural life.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Political officials could now speak directly to millions of citizens.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] One of the first to take advantage of this was American president Franklin Roosevelt, who became famous for his fireside chats during the Great Depression.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, broadcasting also provided the means to use propaganda as a powerful government tool, and contributed to the rise of fascist and communist ideologies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In the 1940s, two new broadcast media, FM radio and television, began to provide extensive competition with the established broadcasting services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The AM radio industry suffered a serious loss of audience and advertising revenue, and coped by developing new strategies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Instead of live music, most stations began playing less expensive recorded music.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In the late 1960s and 1970s, top 40 rock and roll stations in the U.S. and Canada such as WABC and CHUM transmitted highly processed and extended audio to 11 kHz, successfully attracting huge audiences.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In the late 1970s, spurred by the exodus of musical programming to FM stations, the AM radio industry in the United States developed technology for broadcasting in stereo.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Other nations adopted AM stereo, most commonly choosing Motorola's C-QUAM, and in 1993, the United States also made the C-QUAM system its standard, after a period allowing four different standards to compete.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The selection of a single standard improved acceptance of AM stereo, however overall there was limited adoption of AM stereo worldwide, and interest declined after 1990.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] With the continued migration of AM stations away from music to news, sports, and talk formats, receiver manufacturers saw little reason to adopt the more expensive stereo tuners, and thus radio stations have little incentive to upgrade to stereo transmission.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] This sometimes results in the sale of the transmitter site, with the station relocating to a more distant shared site using significantly less power, or completely shutting down operations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The ongoing development of alternative transmission systems, including DAB, satellite radio, and HD radio, continued the decline of the popularity of the traditional broadcast technologies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] These new options, including the introduction of Internet streaming, particularly resulted in the reduction of shortwave transmissions, as international broadcasters found ways to reach their audiences more easily.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However the United States Congress has introduced a bill to require all vehicles sold in the US to have an AM receiver to receive emergency broadcasts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The FM broadcast band was established in 1941 in the United States, and at the time some suggested that the AM band would soon be eliminated.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1948, wide-band FM's inventor, Edwin H.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Since then the AM band's share of the audience has continued to decline.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1987, the elimination of the Fairness Doctrine requirement meant that talk shows, which were commonly carried by AM stations, could adopt a more focused presentation on controversial topics, without the distraction of having to provide airtime for any contrasting opinions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In addition, satellite distribution made it possible for programs to be economically carried on a national scale.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The introduction of nationwide talk shows, most prominently Rush Limbaugh's beginning in 1988, was sometimes credited with "saving" AM radio.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, these stations tended to attract older listeners who were of lesser interest to advertisers, and AM radio's audience share continued to erode.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1961, the FCC adopted a single standard for FM stereo transmissions, which was widely credited with enhancing FM's popularity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Developing the technology for AM broadcasting in stereo was challenging due to the need to limit the transmissions to a 20 kHz bandwidth, while also making the transmissions backward compatible with existing non-stereo receivers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1990, the FCC authorized an AM stereo standard developed by Magnavox, but two years later revised its decision to instead approve four competing implementations, saying it would "let the marketplace decide" which was best.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The lack of a common standard resulted in consumer confusion and increased the complexity and cost of producing AM stereo receivers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 1993, the FCC again revised its policy, by selecting C-QUAM as the sole AM stereo implementation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] On June 8, 1988, an International Telecommunication Union (ITU)-sponsored conference held at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, adopted provisions, effective July 1, 1990, to extend the upper end of the Region 2 AM broadcast band, by adding ten frequencies which spanned from 1610 kHz to 1700 kHz.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] At this time it was suggested that as many as 500 U.S. stations could be assigned to the new frequencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] On April 12, 1990, the FCC voted to begin the process of populating the expanded band, with the main priority being the reduction of interference on the existing AM band, by transferring selected stations to the new frequencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] It was now estimated that the expanded band could accommodate around 300 U.S. stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, it turned out that the number of possible station reassignments was much lower, with a 2006 accounting reporting that, out of 4,758 licensed U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] AM stations, only 56 were now operating on the expanded band.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] HD Radio is a digital audio broadcasting method developed by iBiquity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 2007, nighttime operation was also authorized.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The number of hybrid mode AM stations is not exactly known, because the FCC does not keep track of the stations employing the system, and some authorized stations have later turned it off.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] But as of 2020, the commission estimated that fewer than 250 AM stations were transmitting hybrid mode signals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Despite the various actions, AM band audiences continued to contract, and the number of stations began to slowly decline.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] A 2009 FCC review reported that "The story of AM radio over the last 50 years has been a transition from being the dominant form of audio entertainment for all age groups to being almost non-existent to the youngest demographic groups.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Among persons aged 12–24, AM accounts for only 4% of listening, while FM accounts for 96%.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Among persons aged 25–34, AM accounts for only 9% of listening, while FM accounts for 91%.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 2009, the FCC made a major regulatory change, when it adopted a policy allowing AM stations to simulcast over FM translator stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Translators had previously been available only to FM broadcasters, in order to increase coverage in fringe areas.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Their assignment for use by AM stations was intended to approximate the station's daytime coverage, which in cases where the stations reduced power at night, often resulted in expanded nighttime coverage.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Although the translator stations are not permitted to originate programming when the "primary" AM station is broadcasting, they are permitted to do so during nighttime hours for AM stations licensed for daytime-only operation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Prior to the adoption of the new policy, as of March 18, 2009, the FCC had issued 215 Special Temporary Authority grants for FM translators relaying AM stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] After creation of the new policy, by 2011, there were approximately 500 in operation, and as of 2020, approximately 2,800 of the 4,570 licensed AM stations were rebroadcasting on one or more FM translators.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 2009, the FCC stated that "We do not intend to allow these cross-service translators to be used as surrogates for FM stations".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, based on station slogans, especially in the case of recently adopted musical formats, in most cases the expectation is that listeners will primarily be tuning into the FM signal rather than the nominally "primary" AM station.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] A 2020 review noted that "for many owners, keeping their AM stations on the air now is pretty much just about retaining their FM translator footprint rather than keeping the AM on the air on its own merits".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In 2018, the FCC, led by then-Commission Chairman Ajit Pai, proposed greatly reducing signal protection for 50 kW Class A "clear channel" stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] This would allow co-channel secondary stations to operate with higher powers, especially at night.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] However, the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) expressed concerns that this would reduce the effectiveness of emergency communications.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] In May 2023, a bipartisan group of lawmakers in the United States introduced legislation making it illegal for automakers to eliminate AM radio from their cars.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The lawmakers argue that AM radio is an important tool for public safety due to being a component of the Emergency Alert System (EAS).
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] Some automakers have been eliminating AM radio from their electric vehicles (EVs) due to interference from the electric motors, but the lawmakers argue that this is a safety risk and that car owners should have access to AM radio regardless of the type of vehicle they drive.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] The proposed legislation would require all new vehicles to include AM radio at no additional charge, and it would also require automakers that have already eliminated AM radio to inform customers of alternatives.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p01] DRM30 is another standard to broadcast on the AM bands, with implementation in India and China, among other countries.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] AM radio technology is simpler than later transmission systems.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] An AM receiver detects amplitude variations in the radio waves at a particular frequency, then amplifies changes in the signal voltage to operate a loudspeaker or earphone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In large urban centers, AM radio signals can be severely disrupted by metal structures and tall buildings.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] As a result, AM radio tends to do best in areas where FM frequencies are in short supply, or in thinly populated or mountainous areas where FM coverage is poor.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Great care must be taken to avoid mutual interference between stations operating on the same frequency.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In general, an AM transmission needs to be about 20 times stronger than an interfering signal to avoid a reduction in quality, in contrast to FM signals, where the "capture effect" means that the dominant signal needs to only be about twice as strong as the interfering one.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] To allow room for more stations on the mediumwave broadcast band in the United States, in June 1989, the FCC adopted a National Radio Systems Committee (NRSC) standard that limited maximum transmitted audio bandwidth to 10.2 kHz, limiting occupied bandwidth to 20.4 kHz.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] The former audio limitation was 15 kHz resulting in bandwidth of 30 kHz.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Another common limitation on AM fidelity is the result of receiver design, although some efforts have been made to improve this, notably through the AMAX standards adopted in the United States.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] AM broadcasts are used on several frequency bands.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] The allocation of these bands is governed by the ITU's Radio Regulations and, on the national level, by each country's telecommunications administration (the FCC in the U.S., for example) subject to international agreements.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] The frequency ranges given here are those that are allocated to stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Because of the bandwidth taken up by the sidebands, the range allocated for the band as a whole is usually about 5 kHz wider on either side.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Most of the earliest broadcasting experiments took place on longwave frequencies; however, complaints about interference from existing services, particularly the military, led to most broadcasting moving to higher frequencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Most broadcast services use AM transmissions, although some use a modified version of AM such as Single-sideband modulation (SSB) or an AM-compatible version of SSB such as "SSB with carrier reinserted".
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, the United States evaluated options for the establishment of broadcasting stations using much higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In October 1937, the FCC announced a second band of AM stations, consisting of 75 channels spanning from 41.02 to 43.98 MHz, which were informally called *Apex*.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] The 40 kHz spacing between adjacent frequencies was four times that of the 10 kHz spacing used on the standard AM broadcast band, which reduced adjacent-frequency interference, and provided more bandwidth for high-fidelity programming.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] However, this band was eliminated effective on January 1, 1941, after the FCC determined that establishing a band of FM stations was preferable.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, starting with "The Brown Network" at Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, a very low power broadcasting method known as carrier current was developed, and mostly adopted on U.S. college campuses.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In this approach AM broadcast signals are distributed over electric power lines, which radiate a signal receivable at a short distance from the lines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In Switzerland a system known as "wire broadcasting" (*Telefonrundspruch* in German) transmitted AM signals over telephone lines in the longwave band until 1998, when it was shut down.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In the UK, Rediffusion was an early pioneer of AM radio cable distribution.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Hybrid digital broadcast systems, which combine (mono analog) AM transmission with digital sidebands, have started to be used around the world.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] In the United States, iBiquity's proprietary HD Radio has been adopted and approved by the FCC for medium wave transmissions, while Digital Radio Mondiale is a more open effort often used on the shortwave bands, and can be used alongside many AM broadcasts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Both of these standards are capable of broadcasting audio of significantly greater fidelity than that of standard AM with current bandwidth limitations, and a theoretical frequency response of 0–16 kHz, in addition to stereo sound and text data.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Some microbroadcasters, especially those in the United States operating under the FCC's Part 15 rules, and pirate radio operators on mediumwave and shortwave, achieve greater range than possible on the FM band.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] On mediumwave these stations often transmit on 1610 kHz to 1710 kHz.
[src:unintentional-radiator/am-radio-p02] Microbroadcasting and pirate radio have generally been supplanted by streaming audio on the Internet, but some schools and hobbyists still use LPAM transmissions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The diary was one of the first methods of recording information.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] However, this is prone to mistakes, forgetfulness and subjectivity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Data is collected down to the level of listener opinion of individual songs cross-referenced against age, race, and economic status in listening sessions sponsored by oldies- and mix-formatted stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] IBOPE was the first real-time service for audience measurement in the world, beginning in São Paulo in 1942.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The audience measurement of U.S. television has relied on sampling to obtain estimated audience sizes in which advertisers determine the value of such acquisitions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] According to *The Television Will Be Revolutionized*, Amanda D.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Lotz writes that during the 1960s and 1970s, Nielsen Media Research introduced the Storage Instantaneous Audimeter, a device that sent daily viewing information to the company's computers using phone lines and made national daily ratings available by 1973.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Although the audimeters did not supply sufficient information about audience demographics, it allowed Nielsen to establish diary reports that presented insight into the audience.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] According to Lotz, the Nielsen sample included approximately 1,700 audimeter homes and a rotating panel of approximately 850 diary respondents.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Nielsen was the controlling factor of audience measurement for national network television.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Networks blamed Nielsen for inaccurate rating measurements in the mid-2000s, and the company implemented its automated Local People Meter (LPM) technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The LPM marked the shift from active, diary-based local measurement to passive, meter-monitored measurement of local markets.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Technologically, the LPM is similar to the original Nielsen People Meter; the key advance was that the LPM provided accurate measurements of local markets.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The LPM system has allowed the industry to measure year-round, rather than the quarterly "sweeps" periods.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Researchers believed that the LPM more accurately reported the full range of programming watched, including channel-surfing.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Arbitron's Portable People Meter uses a microphone to pick up and record subaudible tones embedded in broadcasts by an encoder on each station or network, and has been used to track in-store radio.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The introduction of digital terrestrial television (DTT) complicates audience measurement.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] In a multisignal context, with new content in front of technological convergence, the correct representation of viewing behaviors faces methodological challenges.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] New methodologies (audio or video matching, watermarking) are needed to measure digital television audiences.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Measurement with audimeters faces the dual challenges of analog and digital measurement in a mixed television broadcast.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Because of the Internet, many businesses can sell outside their local markets.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] This helps them offer niche items that would face challenges in finding customers in their specific market area.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] In the *Journal of Advertising Research*, Chris Anderson writes: "For some internet-based businesses, locality no longer regulates the market." Offered wider choices, consumers award fewer of their "votes" to the big hits and more to specialized niche choices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] According to Anderson, people always wanted more choices but their desires were obscured by distribution bottlenecks imposed by cost or locality.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] New digital technology initially complicated in-home measurement systems.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The DVR seemed incompatible with a Nielsen box, which was designed to measure the frequency of a television signal to ascertain the channel being viewed.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Since a DVR always produces the same frequency, an active-passive (A/P) meter could be developed to read audio tracks of a particular program instead of the frequency of the television signal.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Other challenges to the industry were digital cable, the Internet, and viewing devices other than televisions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] As new ways of measurement became available and users could be monitored for content and use, concern arose that sampling techniques might become obsolete.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The increasing fragmentation of viewing with different technologies posed difficulties in reporting viewer numbers for content.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Nielsen began rolling out its "anytime anywhere media measurement" initiative in 2010, which includes DVR views in its television figures.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] GTAM (Global Television Audience Metering) is based on the development of audience-metering technology to deal with the challenges in measuring the viewing behavior of consumer households across several platforms (TV, Internet, mobile devices).
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] A/P meters would be replaced by GTAM meters, which were expected to use a combination of active and passive measurement technologies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Unlike A/P meters, however, they would not require a physical connection to a media device.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] MediaWiki software can be equipped with the HitCounters extension as a form of audience measurement and determining wikiFactor, a rough measurement of a wiki website's popularity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] With the increased popularity of webinars and video conferencing due to the remote work requirements of the COVID-19 pandemic, a set of direct and anonymous audience engagement tools such as Mentimeter and Actymeter became popular.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Nielsen//NetRatings measures Internet and digital media audiences with telephone and Internet surveys.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Nielsen BuzzMetrics measures consumer-generated media.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Other companies collecting information on Internet use include comScore, Wakoopa, and Hitwise, which measure hits on Internet pages.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Visible Measures focuses on measuring online video consumption and distribution across all video advertising and content.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] GfK's Cross Media Measurement Solutions measures offline sales after TV, Internet, and mobile exposure.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Sightcorp, TruMedia, Quividi, relEYEble, stickyPiXEL, Cognitec, goCount and CognoVision provide real-time audience data, including size, attention span and demographics, using video analytics to detect, track and classify viewers of digital displays.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Networked Insights measures online audiences, and released a report ranking television shows by social-media interaction.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] According to the study, half of the shows on Networked Insights' top-10 list did not appear on the Nielsen Media Research (NMR) list.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The demographic or "demos" of a show's audience is measured, in ten year age bands (except for kids and teens).
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Advertisers typically look to the results in the "key demo" of adults aged 25 to 54, who are thought to have the most disposable income, or 18 to 24, who are thought to not yet have established brand loyalties.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] A ratings point is a measure of viewership of a television show.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] One television ratings point (Rtg or TVR) represents one percent of television households in the surveyed area in a given minute.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] In 2004, there were an estimated 109.6 million television households in the United States; one national ratings point represented 1,096,000 households for the 2004–05 season.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] When used for a broadcast program, the average rating for the duration of the show is typically given.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Ratings points are often used for specific demographics, rather than households.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] For example, a ratings point for the key 25- to 54-year-old demographic is equivalent to one percent of all 25- to 54-year-olds in the country.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] A Rtg or TVR differs from a share point in being the percentage of all households; a share point is one percent of all households watching television at the time.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The share of a broadcast is often significantly higher than the rating, especially when overall TV viewing is low.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] A low share may lead to the cancellation of a TV program.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Gross rating points (GRPs) or target rating points (TRPs) are chiefly used to measure the performance of TV-based advertising campaigns, and are the sum of the TVRs of each commercial spot of the campaign.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] An ad campaign might require a certain number of GRPs in a particular demographic for the duration of the campaign.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The GRP of a campaign is the percentage of viewers multiplied by the average number of ads viewed.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Net reach is the total of all audiences exposed to a vehicle, excluding duplicate viewership.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Standard audience surveys collect data on audience size and basic demographics.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Audience quality is inferred from an audience's demographic profile, but do not measure audience engagement.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Audience-research methods were questioned during the 1990s with the arrival of new media, particularly digital media, and changes in public media habits.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] People meters, which recorded household viewing by noting the station to which a TV was tuned, failed to capture new viewing habits such as recording programs for playback at a later time or watching a podcast or download on a device such as a tablet or computer.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Video on Demand (VoD) enables consumers to decide when to watch programs, and smartphones enable consumers to choose where to access content.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Media research companies have been forced to devise new methodologies capable of tracking new and unprecedented viewing habits across a diverse range of different platforms.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Audiences often use several media at the same time; a teenager might be plugged into a radio with earphones while working on the Internet, where they are scanning online newspapers and magazines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Media research companies were poorly equipped for the challenge of simultaneous consumption across several platforms, but is slowly adapting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Data collected by people meters is available the morning after programs have aired, but data collected in diaries requires more time to analyse.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Radio surveys, still used for radio ratings in a number of countries, are normally available quarterly.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The time lag in reporting fails to give advertisers sufficient lead time to take corrective action during a campaign.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Other questions have been raised about diary-based data-collection methods.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The expectation that diarists participating in a radio sample will accurately record their listening at 15-minute intervals has been challenged.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Surveying listeners for preferences has been criticised as inflexible.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Listeners complain that radio lacks variety and depth, but measurement methods facilitate further refinement of already-minutely-programmed formats rather than an overhaul.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] In the US, listeners hear old favorites rather than new music.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Data obtained by some audience-measurement methods is detailed for individual songs and how they are reacted to by each age, racial, and economic group the station seeks to attract.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] This approach leads to recognizable songs (such as those by the Beatles) which score well with a cross-section of listeners.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] In most countries, the advertising industry endorses a media-research company as its provider of audience measurement.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] The methodology used by the provider becomes known as the "industry currency" for audience measurement.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Industry members fund audience research and share the findings.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] In a few countries where the industry is fragmented or where there is no industry association, two or more competing organisations may provide audience measurement services; such countries are said to have no industry currency.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Four methods of data collection are used to survey broadcast audiences: interviews, diaries, meters, and scanning and modelling.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] Research companies use different methodologies, depending on where (and when) media is used and the cost of data collection.
[src:unintentional-radiator/audience-measurement] All methods involve sampling: taking a representative sample of the population, recording media use, and extrapolating it to the general population.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] A **cable channel** (sometimes known as a **cable network**) is a television network available via cable television.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Many of the same channels are distributed through satellite television.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Alternative terms include *non-broadcast channel* or *programming service*, the latter being mainly used in legal contexts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] In 1968, 6.4% of Americans had cable television.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] By 1988, 52.8% of all households were using cable.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The number further increased to 62.4% in 1994.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] To receive cable television at a given location, cable distribution lines must be available on the local utility poles or underground utility lines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Coaxial cable brings the signal to the customer's building through a service drop, an overhead or underground cable.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] If the subscriber's building does not have a cable service drop, the cable company will install one.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The standard cable used in the U.S. is RG-6, which has a 75 ohm impedance, and connects with a type F connector.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The cable company's portion of the wiring usually ends at a distribution box on the building exterior, and built-in cable wiring in the walls usually distributes the signal to jacks in different rooms to which televisions are connected.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Multiple cables to different rooms are split off the incoming cable with a small device called a splitter.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] There are two standards for cable television: older analog cable, and newer digital cable, which can carry data signals used by digital television receivers such as high-definition television (HDTV) equipment.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] All cable companies in the United States have switched to or are in the course of switching to digital cable television since it was first introduced in the late 1990s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] A cable from the jack in the wall is attached to the input of the box, and an output cable from the box is attached to the television, usually the RF-IN or composite input on older TVs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Since the set-top box only decodes the single channel that is being watched, each television in the house requires a separate box.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Some unencrypted channels, usually traditional over-the-air broadcast networks, can be displayed without a receiver box.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Older analog television sets are *cable ready* and can receive the old analog cable without a set-top box.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] To receive digital cable channels on an analog television set, even unencrypted ones, requires a different type of box, a digital television adapter supplied by the cable company or purchased by the subscriber.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Another new distribution method that takes advantage of the low-cost, high-quality DVB distribution to residential areas, uses TV gateways to convert the DVB-C, DVB-C2 stream to IP for distribution of TV over an IP network in the home.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Many cable companies offer internet access through DOCSIS.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Many channels can be transmitted through one coaxial cable by a technique called frequency division multiplexing.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At the headend, each television channel is translated to a different frequency.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] By giving each channel a different frequency *slot* on the cable, the separate television signals do not interfere with each other.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At an outdoor cable box on the subscriber's residence, the company's service drop cable is connected to cables distributing the signal to different rooms in the building.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At each television, the subscriber's television or a set-top box provided by the cable company translates the desired channel back to its original frequency (baseband), and it is displayed onscreen.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Due to widespread cable theft in earlier analog systems, the signals are typically encrypted on modern digital cable systems, and the set-top box must be activated by an activation code sent by the cable company before it will function, which is only sent after the subscriber signs up.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] If the subscriber fails to pay their bill, the cable company can send a signal to deactivate the subscriber's box, preventing reception.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] There are also usually upstream channels on the cable to send data from the customer box to the cable headend, for advanced features such as requesting pay-per-view shows or movies, cable internet access, and cable telephone service.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The downstream channels occupy a band of frequencies from approximately 50 MHz to 1 GHz, while the upstream channels occupy frequencies of 5 to 42 MHz.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Subscribers can choose from several levels of service, with premium packages including more channels but costing a higher rate.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At the local headend, the feed signals from the individual television channels are received by dish antennas from communication satellites.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Additional local channels, such as local broadcast television stations, educational channels from local colleges, and community access channels devoted to local governments (PEG channels) are usually included on the cable service.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Commercial advertisements for local businesses are also inserted in the programming at the headend (the individual channels, which are distributed nationally, also have their own nationally oriented commercials).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Modern cable systems are large, with a single network and headend often serving an entire metropolitan area.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Most systems use hybrid fiber-coaxial (HFC) distribution; this means the trunklines that carry the signal from the headend to local neighborhoods are optical fiber to provide greater bandwidth and also extra capacity for future expansion.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At the headend, the electrical signal is translated into an optical signal and sent through the fiber.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The fiber trunkline goes to several *distribution hubs*, from which multiple fibers fan out to carry the signal to boxes called *optical nodes* in local communities.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At the optical node, the optical signal is translated back into an electrical signal and carried by coaxial cable distribution lines on utility poles, from which cables branch out to a series of signal amplifiers and line extenders.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] These devices carry the signal to customers via passive RF devices called taps.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The very first cable networks were operated locally, notably in 1936 by Rediffusion in London in the United Kingdom and the same year in Berlin in Germany, notably for the Olympic Games, and from 1948 onwards in the United States and Switzerland.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] This type of local cable network was mainly used to relay terrestrial channels in geographical areas poorly served by terrestrial television signals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Cable television began in the United States as a commercial business in 1950s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The early systems simply received weak (broadcast) channels, amplified them, and sent them over unshielded wires to the subscribers, limited to a community or to adjacent communities.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The receiving antenna would be taller than any individual subscriber could afford, thus bringing in stronger signals; in hilly or mountainous terrain, it would be placed at a high elevation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] At the outset, cable systems only served smaller communities without television stations of their own, and which could not easily receive signals from stations in cities because of distance or hilly terrain.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] In Canada, however, communities with their own signals were fertile cable markets, as viewers wanted to receive American signals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Rarely, as in the college town of Alfred, New York, U.S. cable systems retransmitted Canadian channels.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] (There were frequency gaps between 4 and 5, and between 6 and 7, which allowed both to be used in the same city).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] As equipment improved, all twelve channels could be utilized, except where a local VHF television station broadcast.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Local broadcast channels were not usable for signals deemed to be a priority, but technology allowed low-priority signals to be placed on such channels by synchronizing their blanking intervals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] TVs were unable to reconcile these blanking intervals and the slight changes due to travel through a medium, causing ghosting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The bandwidth of the amplifiers was also limited, meaning frequencies over 250 MHz were difficult to transmit to distant portions of the coaxial network, and UHF channels could not be used at all.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Initially, UHF broadcast stations were at a disadvantage because the standard TV sets in use at the time were unable to receive their channels.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] With the passage of the All-Channel Receiver Act in 1964, all new television sets were required to include a UHF tuner; nonetheless, it would still take a few years for UHF stations to become competitive.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Before being added to the cable box itself, these midband channels were used for early incarnations of pay TV, e.g.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The Z Channel (Los Angeles) and HBO but transmitted in the clear i.e. not scrambled as standard TV sets of the period could not pick up the signal nor could the average consumer *de-tune* the normal stations to be able to receive it.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Once tuners that could receive select mid-band and super-band channels began to be incorporated into standard television sets, broadcasters were forced to either install scrambling circuitry or move these signals further out of the range of reception for early cable-ready TVs and VCRs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] However, once consumer sets had the ability to receive all 181 FCC-allocated channels, premium broadcasters were left with no choice but to scramble.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The descrambling circuitry was often published in electronics hobby magazines such as *Popular Science* and *Popular Electronics* allowing anybody with anything more than a rudimentary knowledge of broadcast electronics to be able to build their own and receive the programming without cost.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Later, the cable operators began to carry FM radio stations, and encouraged subscribers to connect their FM stereo sets to cable.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Before stereo and bilingual TV sound became common, Pay-TV channel sound was added to the FM stereo cable line-ups.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] About this time, operators expanded beyond the 12-channel dial to use the *midband* and *superband* VHF channels adjacent to the *high band* 7–13 of North American television frequencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Some operators as in Cornwall, Ontario, used a dual distribution network with Channels 2–13 on each of the two cables.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] During the 1980s, United States regulations not unlike public, educational, and government access (PEG) created the beginning of cable-originated live television programming.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] As cable penetration increased, numerous cable-only TV stations were launched, many with their own news bureaus that could provide more immediate and more localized content than that provided by the nearest network newscast.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Such stations may use similar on-air branding as that used by the nearby broadcast network affiliate, but since these stations do not broadcast over the air and are not regulated by the FCC, their call signs are meaningless.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Many live local programs with local interests were subsequently created all over the United States in most major television markets in the early 1980s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] This evolved into today's many cable-only broadcasts of diverse programming, including cable-only produced television movies and miniseries.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Cable specialty channels, starting with channels oriented to show movies and large sporting or performance events, diversified further, and narrowcasting became common.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] By the late 1980s, cable-only signals outnumbered broadcast signals on cable systems, some of which by this time had expanded beyond 35 channels.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] By the mid-1980s in Canada, cable operators were allowed by the regulators to enter into distribution contracts with cable networks on their own.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] By the 1990s, tiers became common, with customers able to subscribe to different tiers to obtain different selections of additional channels above the basic selection.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] By subscribing to additional tiers, customers could get specialty channels, movie channels, and foreign channels.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Large cable companies used addressable descramblers to limit access to premium channels for customers not subscribing to higher tiers; however, the above magazines often published workarounds for that technology as well.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Although for a time in the 1980s and 1990s, television receivers and VCRs were equipped to receive the mid-band and super-band channels.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Because the descrambling circuitry was for a time present in these tuners, depriving the cable operator of much of their revenue, such cable-ready tuners are rarely used now, requiring a return to the set-top boxes used from the 1970s onward.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The digital television transition in the United States has put all signals, broadcast and cable, into digital form, rendering analog cable television service a rarity, found in an ever-dwindling number of markets.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Analog television sets are accommodated, their tuners mostly obsolete and dependent entirely on the set-top box.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Cable television is mostly available in North America, Europe, Australia, Asia and South America.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Cable television has had little success in Africa, as it is not cost-effective to lay cables in sparsely populated areas.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Multichannel multipoint distribution service, a microwave-based system, may be used instead.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Coaxial cables are capable of bi-directional carriage of signals as well as the transmission of large amounts of data.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Cable television signals use only a portion of the bandwidth available over coaxial lines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] This leaves plenty of space available for other digital services such as cable internet, cable telephony and wireless services, using both unlicensed and licensed spectra.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Broadband internet access is achieved over coaxial cable by using cable modems to convert the network data into a type of digital signal that can be transferred over coaxial cable.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] One problem with some cable systems is that the older amplifiers placed along the cable routes are unidirectional; thus, in order to allow for uploading of data, the customer would need to use an analog telephone modem to provide for the upstream connection.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] This limited the upstream speed to 31.2 kbit/s and prevented the always-on convenience broadband internet typically provides.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Many large cable systems have upgraded or are upgrading their equipment to allow for bi-directional signals, thus allowing for greater upload speed and always-on convenience, though these upgrades are expensive.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] In North America, Australia and Europe, many cable operators have already introduced cable telephone service, which operates just like existing fixed line operators.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The biggest obstacle to cable telephone service is the need for nearly 100% reliable service for emergency calls.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] One of the standards available for digital cable telephony, PacketCable, seems to be the most promising and able to work with the quality of service (QOS) demands of traditional analog plain old telephone service (POTS) service.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The biggest advantage to digital cable telephone service is similar to the advantage of digital cable, namely that data can be compressed, resulting in much less bandwidth used than a dedicated analog circuit-switched service.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Other advantages include better voice quality and integration to a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) network, providing cheap or unlimited nationwide and international calling.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] In many cases, digital cable telephone service is separate from cable modem service being offered by many cable companies and does not rely on Internet Protocol (IP) traffic or the Internet.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] Traditional cable television providers and traditional telecommunication companies increasingly compete in providing voice, video and data services to residences.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cable-television] The combination of television, telephone and Internet access is commonly called *triple play*, regardless of whether CATV or telcos offer it.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A **mobile phone** or **cell phone** is a portable wireless telephone that allows users to make and receive calls over a radio frequency link while moving within a designated telephone service area, unlike fixed-location phones (landline phones).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This radio frequency link connects to the switching systems of a mobile phone operator, providing access to the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Modern mobile telephony relies on a cellular network architecture, which is why mobile phones are often referred to as 'cell phones' in North America.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Beyond traditional voice communication, digital mobile phones have evolved to support a wide range of additional services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] These include text messaging, multimedia messaging, email, and internet access (via LTE, 5G NR or Wi-Fi), as well as short-range wireless technologies like Bluetooth, infrared, and ultra-wideband (UWB).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones also support a variety of multimedia capabilities, such as digital photography, video recording, and gaming.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In addition, they enable multimedia playback and streaming, including video content, as well as radio and television streaming.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Furthermore, mobile phones offer satellite-based services, such as navigation and messaging, as well as business applications and payment solutions (via scanning QR codes or near-field communication (NFC)).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones offering only basic features are often referred to as feature phones (slang: *dumbphones*), while those with advanced computing power are known as smartphones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first handheld mobile phone was demonstrated by Martin Cooper of Motorola in New York City on 3 April 1973, using a handset weighing c.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1979, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) launched the world's first cellular network in Japan.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1983, the DynaTAC 8000x was the first commercially available handheld mobile phone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] From 1993 to 2024, worldwide mobile phone subscriptions grew to over 9.1 billion; enough to provide one for every person on Earth.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 2024, the top smartphone manufacturers worldwide were Samsung, Apple and Xiaomi; smartphone sales represented about 50 percent of total mobile phone sales.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] For feature phones as of 2016, the top-selling brands were Samsung, Nokia and Alcatel.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones are considered an important human invention as they have been one of the most widely used and sold pieces of consumer technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The growth in popularity has been rapid in some places; for example, in the UK, the total number of mobile phones overtook the number of houses in 1999.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Today, mobile phones are globally ubiquitous, and in almost half the world's countries, over 90% of the world population, or approximately 7.2 billion people, owns at least one.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] "Mobile phone" is the most common English-language term, while the term "cell phone" is in more common use in North America – both are in essence shorter versions of "*mobile telephone*" and "*cellular telephone*", respectively.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Often in colloquial terms it is referred to as simply **phone**, **mobile** or **cell**.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A number of alternative words have also been used to describe a mobile phone, most of which have fallen out of use, including: "*mobile handset*", "*wireless phone*", "*mobile terminal*", "*cellular device*", "*hand phone*", and "*pocket phone*".
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A handheld mobile radio telephone service was envisioned in the early stages of radio engineering.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1917, Finnish inventor Eric Tigerstedt filed a patent for a "pocket-size folding telephone with a very thin carbon microphone".
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Early predecessors of cellular phones included analog radio communications from ships and trains.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The race to create truly portable telephone devices began after World War II, with developments taking place in many countries.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The advances in mobile telephony have been traced in successive "generations", starting with the early zeroth-generation (0G) services, such as Bell System's Mobile Telephone Service and its successor, the Improved Mobile Telephone Service.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] These 0G systems were not cellular, supported a few simultaneous calls, and were very expensive.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phone technology has progressed significantly since its origins, evolving from large car-mounted systems to compact, handheld devices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Early mobile phones required vehicle installation due to their size and power needs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A major breakthrough came in 1973, when the first handheld cellular mobile phone was demonstrated by John F.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mitchell and Martin Cooper of Motorola, using a handset weighing 2 kilograms (4.4 lb).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Cooper made the first ever call on a cell phone when he called Joel S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first commercial automated cellular network (1G) analog was launched in Japan by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone in 1979.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This was followed in 1981 by the simultaneous launch of the Nordic Mobile Telephone (NMT) system in Denmark, Finland, Norway, and Sweden.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Several other countries then followed in the early to mid-1980s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] These first-generation (1G) systems could support far more simultaneous calls but still used analog cellular technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1991, the second-generation (2G) digital cellular technology was launched in Finland by Radiolinja on the GSM standard.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This sparked competition in the sector as the new operators challenged the incumbent 1G network operators.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The GSM standard is a European initiative expressed at the CEPT ("Conférence Européenne des Postes et Telecommunications", European Postal and Telecommunications conference).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The Franco-German R&D cooperation demonstrated the technical feasibility, and in 1987, a Memorandum of Understanding was signed between 13 European countries that agreed to launch a commercial service by 1991.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first version of the GSM standard had 6,000 pages.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The IEEE and RSE awarded Thomas Haug and Philippe Dupuis the 2018 James Clerk Maxwell medal for their contributions to the first digital mobile telephone standard.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 2018, the GSM was used by over 5 billion people in over 220 countries.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The GSM (2G) has evolved into 3G, 4G and 5G.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The standardization body for GSM started at the CEPT Working Group GSM (Group Special Mobile) in 1982 under the umbrella of CEPT.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1988, ETSI was established, and all CEPT standardization activities were transferred to ETSI.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Working Group GSM became Technical Committee GSM.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1991, it became Technical Committee SMG (Special Mobile Group) when ETSI tasked the committee with UMTS (3G).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In addition to transmitting voice over digital signals, the 2G network introduced data services for mobile, starting with SMS text messages, then expanding to Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS), and mobile internet with a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 384 kbit/s (48 kB/s).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 2001, the third-generation (3G) was launched in Japan by NTT DoCoMo on the WCDMA standard.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This was followed by 3.5G or 3G+ enhancements based on the high-speed packet access (HSPA) family, allowing UMTS networks to have higher data transfer speeds and capacity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] 3G is able to provide mobile broadband access of several Mbit/s to smartphones and mobile modems in laptop computers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This ensures it can be applied to mobile Internet access, VoIP, video calls, and sending large e-mail messages, as well as watching videos, typically in standard-definition quality.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] By 2009, it had become clear that, at some point, 3G networks would be overwhelmed by the growth of bandwidth-intensive applications, such as streaming media.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Consequently, the industry began looking to data-optimized fourth-generation (4G) technologies, with the promise of speed improvements up to tenfold over existing 3G technologies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first publicly available LTE service was launched in Scandinavia by TeliaSonera in 2009.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Deployment of fifth-generation (5G) cellular networks commenced worldwide in 2019.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The term "5G" was originally used in research papers and projects to denote the next major phase in mobile telecommunication standards beyond the 4G/IMT-Advanced standards.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The 3GPP defines 5G as any system that adheres to the 5G NR (5G New Radio) standard.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] 5G can be implemented in low-band, mid-band or high-band millimeter-wave, with download speeds that can achieve gigabit-per-second (Gbit/s) range, aiming for a network latency of 1 ms.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This near-real-time responsiveness and improved overall data performance are crucial for applications like online gaming, augmented and virtual reality, autonomous vehicles, IoT, and critical communication services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Smartphones are defined by their advanced computing capabilities, which include internet connectivity and access to a wide range of applications.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The International Telecommunication Union measures those with Internet connection, which it calls *Active Mobile-Broadband subscriptions* (which includes tablets, etc.).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In developed countries, smartphones have largely replaced earlier mobile technologies, while in developing regions, they account for around 50% of all mobile phone usage.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Feature phone is a term typically used as a retronym to describe mobile phones which are limited in capabilities in contrast to a modern smartphone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Feature phones typically provide voice calling and text messaging functionality, in addition to basic multimedia and Internet capabilities, and other services offered by the user's wireless service provider.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A feature phone has additional functions over and above a basic mobile phone, which is only capable of voice calling and text messaging.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Feature phones and basic mobile phones tend to use a proprietary, custom-designed software and user interface.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] By contrast, smartphones generally use a mobile operating system that often shares common traits across devices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The critical advantage that modern cellular networks have over predecessor systems is the concept of frequency reuse allowing many simultaneous telephone conversations in a given service area.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This allows efficient use of the limited radio spectrum allocated to mobile services, and lets thousands of subscribers converse at the same time within a given geographic area.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Former systems would cover a service area with one or two powerful base stations with a range of up to tens of kilometers' (miles), using only a few sets of radio channels (frequencies).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Once these few channels were in use by customers, no further customers could be served until another user vacated a channel.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] It would be impractical to give every customer a unique channel since there would not be enough bandwidth allocated to the mobile service.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] As well, technical limitations such as antenna efficiency and receiver design limit the range of frequencies a customer unit could use.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A cellular network mobile phone system gets its name from dividing the service area into many small cells, each with a base station with (for example) a useful range on the order of a kilometer (mile).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] These systems have dozens or hundreds of possible channels allocated to them.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] When a subscriber is using a given channel for a telephone connection, that frequency is unavailable for other customers in the local cell and in the adjacent cells.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] However, cells further away can re-use that channel without interference as the subscriber's handset is too far away to be detected.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The transmitter power of each base station is coordinated to efficiently service its own cell, but not to interfere with the cells further away.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The automation systems can control the "hand off" of a customer handset moving between one cell and another so that a call in progress continues without interruption, changing channels if required.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In the earliest mobile phone systems by contrast, all control was done manually; the customer would search for an unoccupied channel and speak to a mobile operator to request connection of a call to a landline number or another mobile.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] At the termination of the call the mobile operator would manually record the billing information.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones communicate with cell towers that are placed to give coverage across a telephone service area, which is divided up into 'cells'.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Each cell uses a different set of frequencies from neighboring cells, and will typically be covered by three towers placed at different locations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The cell towers are usually interconnected to each other and the phone network and the internet by wired connections.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Due to bandwidth limitations each cell will have a maximum number of cell phones it can handle at once.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The cells are therefore sized depending on the expected usage density, and may be much smaller in cities.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In that case much lower transmitter powers are used to avoid broadcasting beyond the cell.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In order to handle the high traffic, multiple towers can be set up in the same area (using different frequencies).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This can be done permanently or temporarily such as at special events or in disasters.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Cell phone companies will bring a truck with equipment to host the abnormally high traffic.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Capacity was further increased when phone companies implemented digital networks.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] With digital, one frequency can host multiple simultaneous calls.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Additionally, short-range Wi-Fi infrastructure is often used by smartphones as much as possible as it offloads traffic from cell networks on to local area networks.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Low-end mobile phones are often referred to as feature phones and offer basic telephony.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Handsets with more advanced computing ability through the use of native software applications are known as smartphones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first GSM phones and many feature phones had NOR flash memory, from which processor instructions could be executed directly in an execute in place architecture and allowed for short boot times.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] With smartphones, NAND flash memory was adopted as it has larger storage capacities and lower costs, but causes longer boot times because instructions cannot be executed from it directly, and must be copied to RAM memory first before execution.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones have central processing units (CPUs), similar to those in computers, but optimised to operate in low power environments.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile CPU performance depends not only on the clock rate (generally given in multiples of hertz) but also the memory hierarchy also greatly affects overall performance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Because of these problems, the performance of mobile phone CPUs is often more appropriately given by scores derived from various standardized tests to measure the real effective performance in commonly used applications.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] One of the main characteristics of phones is the screen.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Depending on the device's type and design, the screen fills most or nearly all of the space on a device's front surface.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Many smartphone displays have an aspect ratio of 16:9, but taller aspect ratios became more common in 2017.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Screen sizes are often measured in diagonal inches or millimeters; feature phones generally have screen sizes below 90 millimetres (3.5 in).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Liquid-crystal displays are the most common; others are IPS, LED, OLED, and AMOLED displays.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Some displays are integrated with pressure-sensitive digitizers, such as those developed by Wacom and Samsung, and Apple's "3D Touch" system.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In sound, smartphones and feature phones vary little.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Some audio-quality enhancing features, such as Voice over LTE and HD Voice, have appeared and are often available on newer smartphones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Sound quality can remain a problem due to the design of the phone, the quality of the cellular network and compression algorithms used in long-distance calls.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Audio quality can be improved using a VoIP application over WiFi.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Cellphones have small speakers so that the user can use a speakerphone feature and talk to a person on the phone without holding it to their ear.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The small speakers can also be used to listen to digital audio files of music or speech or watch videos with an audio component, without holding the phone close to the ear.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The typical lifespan of a mobile phone battery is approximately two to three years, although this varies based on usage patterns, environmental conditions, and overall care.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Most modern mobile phones use lithium-ion (Li-ion) batteries, which are designed to endure between 500 and 2,500 charge cycles.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The exact number of cycles depends on factors such as charging habits, operating temperature, and battery management systems.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Li-ion batteries gradually degrade over time due to chemical aging, leading to reduced capacity and performance, often noticeable after one or two years of regular use.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Unlike older battery types, such as nickel-metal hydride (Ni-MH), Li-ion batteries do not need to be fully discharged to maintain their longevity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In fact, they perform best when kept between 30% and 80% of their full charge.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] While practices such as avoiding excessive heat and minimizing overcharging can help preserve battery health, many modern devices include built-in safeguards.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] These safeguards, typically managed by the phone's internal battery management system (BMS), prevent overcharging by cutting off power once the battery reaches full capacity.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Additionally, most contemporary chargers and devices are designed to regulate charging to minimize stress on the battery.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Therefore, while good charging habits can positively impact battery longevity, most users benefit from these integrated protections, making battery maintenance less of a concern in day-to-day use.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Future mobile phone batteries are expected to utilize advanced technologies such as silicon-carbon (Si/C) batteries and solid-state batteries, which promise to offer higher energy densities, longer lifespans, and improved safety compared to current lithium-ion batteries.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones require a small microchip called a Subscriber Identity Module or SIM card, in order to function.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The SIM card is approximately the size of a small postage stamp and is usually placed underneath the battery in the rear of the unit.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The SIM securely stores the service-subscriber key (IMSI) and the Ki used to identify and authenticate the user of the mobile phone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The SIM card allows users to change phones by simply removing the SIM card from one mobile phone and inserting it into another mobile phone or broadband telephony device, provided that this is not prevented by a SIM lock.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first SIM card was made in 1991 by Munich smart card maker Giesecke & Devrient for the Finnish wireless network operator Radiolinja.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A hybrid mobile phone can hold up to four SIM cards, with a phone having a different device identifier for each SIM Card.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] SIM and R-UIM cards may be mixed together to allow both GSM and CDMA networks to be accessed.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] From 2010 onwards, such phones became popular in emerging markets, and this was attributed to the desire to obtain the lowest calling costs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] When the removal of a SIM card is detected by the operating system, it may deny further operation until a reboot.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Feature phones have basic software platforms whilst smartphones have a fully-featured operating system (commonly abbreviated to an OS), with the two most-used platforms being Android and iOS.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Of the two, Android has been the best-selling system worldwide on smartphones since 2011, and as of March 2025, Android had 71.9% of the overall market share, while iOS had 27.7%.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A mobile app is a computer program designed to run on a mobile device, such as a smartphone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The term "app" is a shortening of the term "software application".
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A common data application on mobile phones is Short Message Service (SMS) text messaging.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first SMS message was sent from a computer to a mobile phone in 1992 in the UK while the first person-to-person SMS from phone to phone was sent in Finland in 1993.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The first mobile news service, delivered via SMS, was launched in Finland in 2000, and subsequently many organizations provided "on-demand" and "instant" news services by SMS.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) was introduced in March 2002.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The introduction of Apple's App Store for the iPhone and iPod Touch in July 2008 popularized manufacturer-hosted online distribution for third-party applications (software and computer programs) focused on a single platform.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] There are a huge variety of apps, including video games, music products and business tools.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Up until that point, smartphone application distribution depended on third-party sources providing applications for multiple platforms, such as GetJar, Handango, Handmark, and PocketGear.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Following the success of the App Store, other smartphone manufacturers launched application stores, such as Google's Android Market (later renamed to the Google Play Store), RIM's BlackBerry App World, or Android-related app stores like Aptoide, Cafe Bazaar, F-Droid, GetJar, and Opera Mobile Store.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In February 2014, 93% of mobile developers were targeting smartphones first for mobile app development.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] As of 2022, the top five manufacturers worldwide were Samsung (21%), Apple (16%), Xiaomi (13%), Oppo (10%), and Vivo (9%).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] From 1983 to 1998, Motorola was market leader in mobile phones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Nokia was the market leader in mobile phones from 1998 to 2012.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In Q1 2012, Samsung surpassed Nokia, selling 93.5 million units as against Nokia's 82.7 million units.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Samsung has retained its top position since then.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Aside from Motorola, European brands such as Nokia, Siemens and Ericsson once held large sway over the global mobile phone market, and many new technologies were pioneered in Europe.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] By 2010, the influence of European companies had significantly decreased due to fierce competition from American and Asian companies, to where most technical innovation had shifted.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Apple and Google, both of the United States, also came to dominate mobile phone software.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The world's largest individual mobile operator by number of subscribers is China Mobile, which has over 902 million mobile phone subscribers as of June 2018.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Over 50 mobile operators have over ten million subscribers each, and over 150 mobile operators had at least one million subscribers by the end of 2009.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 2014, there were more than seven billion mobile phone subscribers worldwide, a number that is expected to keep growing.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones are used for a variety of purposes, such as keeping in touch with family members, for conducting business, and in order to have access to a telephone in the event of an emergency.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Some people carry more than one mobile phone for different purposes, such as for business and personal use.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Multiple SIM cards may be used to take advantage of the benefits of different calling plans.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] For example, a particular plan might provide for cheaper local calls, long-distance calls, international calls, or roaming.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The mobile phone has been used in a variety of diverse contexts in society.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 1998, one of the first examples of distributing and selling media content through the mobile phone was the sale of ringtones by Radiolinja in Finland.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Soon afterwards, other media content appeared, such as news, video games, jokes, horoscopes, TV content and advertising.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Most early content for mobile phones tended to be copies of legacy media, such as banner advertisements or TV news highlight video clips.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Recently, unique content for mobile phones has been emerging, from ringtones and ringback tones to mobisodes, video content that has been produced exclusively for mobile phones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In many countries, mobile phones are used to provide mobile banking services, which may include the ability to transfer cash payments by secure SMS text message.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Kenya's M-PESA mobile banking service, for example, allows customers of the mobile phone operator Safaricom to hold cash balances which are recorded on their SIM cards.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Cash can be deposited or withdrawn from M-PESA accounts at Safaricom retail outlets located throughout the country and can be transferred electronically from person to person and used to pay bills to companies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Branchless banking has also been successful in South Africa and the Philippines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A pilot project in Bali was launched in 2011 by the International Finance Corporation and an Indonesian bank, Bank Mandiri.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile payments were first trialled in Finland in 1998 when two Coca-Cola vending machines in Espoo were enabled to work with SMS payments.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Eventually, the idea spread and in 1999, the Philippines launched the country's first commercial mobile payments systems with mobile operators Globe and Smart.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Some mobile phones can make mobile payments via direct mobile billing schemes, or through contactless payments if the phone and the point of sale support near field communication (NFC).
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Enabling contactless payments through NFC-equipped mobile phones requires the co-operation of manufacturers, network operators, and retail merchants.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones are commonly used to collect location data.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The movements of a mobile phone user can be tracked by their service provider and, if desired, by law enforcement agencies and their governments.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Both the SIM card and the handset can be tracked.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] China has proposed using this technology to track the commuting patterns of Beijing city residents.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In the UK and US, law enforcement and intelligence services use mobile phones to perform surveillance operations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Hackers have been able to track a phone's location, read messages, and record calls, through obtaining a subscriber's phone number.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Studies have shown that around 40–50% of the environmental impact of mobile phones occurs during the manufacture of their printed wiring boards and integrated circuits.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The average user replaces their mobile phone every 11 to 18 months, and the discarded phones then contribute to electronic waste.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phone manufacturers within Europe are subject to the WEEE directive, and Australia has introduced a mobile phone recycling scheme.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Apple Inc. had an advanced robotic disassembler and sorter called Liam specifically for recycling outdated or broken iPhones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] According to the Federal Communications Commission, one out of three robberies involve the theft of a cellular phone.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Police data in San Francisco show that half of all robberies in 2012 were thefts of cellular phones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] An online petition on Change.org, called *Secure our Smartphones*, urged smartphone manufacturers to install kill switches in their devices to make them unusable if stolen.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The petition is part of a joint effort by New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman and San Francisco District Attorney George Gascón and was directed to the CEOs of the major smartphone manufacturers and telecommunication carriers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] On 10 June 2013, Apple announced that it would install a "kill switch" on its next iPhone operating system, due to debut in October 2013.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] All mobile phones have a unique identifier called IMEI.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Anyone can report their phone as lost or stolen with their Telecom Carrier, and the IMEI would be blacklisted with a central registry.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Telecom carriers, depending upon local regulation can or must implement blocking of blacklisted phones in their network.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] There are, however, a number of ways to circumvent a blacklist.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] One method is to send the phone to a country where the telecom carriers are not required to implement the blacklisting and sell it there, another involves altering the phone's IMEI number.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Even so, mobile phones typically have less value on the second-hand market if the phones original IMEI is blacklisted.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Demand for metals used in mobile phones and other electronics fuelled the Second Congo War, which claimed almost 5.5 million lives.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In a 2012 news story, *The Guardian* reported: "In unsafe mines deep underground in eastern Congo, children are working to extract minerals essential for the electronics industry.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The profits from the minerals finance the bloodiest conflict since the second world war; the war has lasted nearly 20 years and has recently flared up again.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] For the last 15 years, the Democratic Republic of the Congo has been a major source of natural resources for the mobile phone industry." The company Fairphone has worked to develop a mobile phone that does not contain conflict minerals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Although these phones are intended to prevent immodesty, some vendors report good sales to adults who prefer the simplicity of the devices; other Orthodox Jews question the need for them.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In Israel, similar phones to kosher phones with restricted features exist to observe the sabbath; under Orthodox Judaism, the use of any electrical device is generally prohibited during this time, other than to save lives, or reduce the risk of death or similar needs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Such phones are approved for use by essential workers, such as health, security, and public service workers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Restrictions on the use of mobile phones are applied in a number of different contexts, often with the goal of health, safety, security or proper functioning of an establishment, or as a matter of etiquette.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phone use while driving, including talking on the phone, texting, or operating other phone features, is common but controversial.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] It is widely considered dangerous due to distracted driving.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Being distracted while operating a motor vehicle has been shown to increase the risk of accidents.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In September 2010, the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) reported that 995 people were killed by drivers distracted by cell phones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In March 2011, a US insurance company, State Farm Insurance, announced the results of a study which showed 19% of drivers surveyed accessed the Internet on a smartphone while driving.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Many jurisdictions prohibit the use of mobile phones while driving.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In Egypt, Israel, Japan, Portugal, and Singapore, both handheld and hands-free use of a mobile phone (which uses a speakerphone) is banned.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In other countries, including the UK and France and in many US states, only handheld phone use is banned while hands-free use is permitted.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A 2011 study reported that over 90% of college students surveyed text (initiate, reply or read) while driving.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The scientific literature on the dangers of driving while sending a text message from a mobile phone, or *texting while driving*, is limited.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A simulation study at the University of Utah found a sixfold increase in distraction-related accidents when texting.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Due to the increasing complexity of mobile phones, they are often more like mobile computers in their available uses.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This has introduced additional difficulties for law enforcement officials when attempting to distinguish one usage from another in drivers using their devices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This is more apparent in countries which ban both handheld and hands-free usage, rather than those which ban handheld use only, as officials cannot easily tell which function of the mobile phone is being used simply by looking at the driver.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This can lead to drivers being stopped for using their device illegally for a phone call when, in fact, they were using the device legally, for example, when using the phone's incorporated controls for car stereo, GPS or satnav.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A 2010 study reviewed the incidence of mobile phone use while cycling and its effects on behaviour and safety.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In 2013, a national survey in the US reported the number of drivers who reported using their cellphones to access the Internet while driving had risen to nearly one of four.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A study conducted by the University of Vienna examined approaches for reducing inappropriate and problematic use of mobile phones, such as using mobile phones while driving.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Accidents involving a driver being distracted by talking on a mobile phone have begun to be prosecuted as negligence similar to speeding.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In the United Kingdom, from 27 February 2007, motorists who are caught using a hand-held mobile phone while driving will have three penalty points added to their license in addition to the fine of £60.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This increase was introduced to try to stem the increase in drivers ignoring the law.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Japan prohibits all mobile phone use while driving, including use of hands-free devices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] New Zealand has banned hand-held cell phone use since 1 November 2009.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Many states in the United States have banned texting on cell phones while driving.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Illinois became the 17th American state to enforce this law.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] As of July 2010, 30 states had banned texting while driving, with Kentucky becoming the most recent addition on 15 July.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Public Health Law Research maintains a list of distracted driving laws in the United States.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] This database of laws provides a comprehensive view of the provisions of laws that restrict the use of mobile communication devices while driving for all 50 states and the District of Columbia between 1992 when first law was passed, through 1 December 2010.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The dataset contains information on 22 dichotomous, continuous or categorical variables including, for example, activities regulated (e.g., texting versus talking, hands-free versus handheld), targeted populations, and exemptions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In the U.S., the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) regulations prohibit the use of mobile phones aboard aircraft in flight.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Contrary to popular misconception, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) does not actually prohibit the use of personal electronic devices (including cell phones) on aircraft.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In Europe, regulations and technology have allowed the limited introduction of the use of passenger mobile phones on some commercial flights, and elsewhere in the world many airlines are moving towards allowing mobile phone use in flight.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Many airlines still do not allow the use of mobile phones on aircraft.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Those that do often ban the use of mobile phones during take-off and landing.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Many passengers are pressing airlines and their governments to allow and deregulate mobile phone use, while some airlines, under the pressure of competition, are also pushing for deregulation or seeking new technology which could solve the present problems.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Official aviation agencies and safety boards are resisting any relaxation of the present safety rules unless and until it can be conclusively shown that it would be safe to do so.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] There are both technical and social factors which make the issues more complex than a simple discussion of safety versus hazard.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Between 2011 and 2019, an estimated 30,000 walking injuries occurred in the US related to using a cellphone, leading to some jurisdictions attempting to ban pedestrians from using their cellphones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Other countries, such as China and the Netherlands, have introduced special lanes for smartphone users to help direct and manage them.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In most jurisdictions, prison inmates are forbidden from possessing mobile phones due to their ability to communicate with the outside world and other security issues.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones are one of the most smuggled items into prisons.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] They provide inmates the ability to make and receive unauthorized phone calls, send email and text messages, use social media, and follow news pertaining to their case, among other forbidden uses.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] As of 2007, some hospitals had banned mobile devices due to a common misconception that their use would create significant electromagnetic interference.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Screen time, the amount of time using a device with a screen, has become an issue for mobile phones since the adaptation of smartphones.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Research is being conducted to show the correlation between screen time and the mental and physical harm in child development.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] To prevent harm, some parents and even governments have placed restrictions on its usage.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] There have been rumors that mobile phone use can cause cancer, but this is a myth.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] While there are rumors of mobile phones causing cancer, there was a study conducted by International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) that stated the there could be an increase risk of brain tumors with the use of smartphones, this is not confirmed.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] They also stated that with the lack of data for the research and the usage periods of 15 years will warrant further research for smartphones and the cause of brain tumors.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] A study by the London School of Economics found that banning mobile phones in schools could increase pupils' academic performance, providing benefits equal to one extra week of schooling per year.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Mobile phones are considered an important human invention as it has been one of the most widely used and sold pieces of consumer technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] They have also become culturally symbolic.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] In Japanese mobile phone culture for example, mobile phones are often decorated with charms.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] They have also become fashion symbols at times.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] The Motorola Razr V3 and LG Chocolate are two examples of devices that were popular for being fashionable while not necessarily focusing on the original purpose of mobile phones, i.e. a device to provide mobile telephony.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Some have also suggested that mobile phones or smartphones are a status symbol.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] For example, a research paper suggested that owning specifically an Apple iPhone was seen to be a status symbol.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] Text messaging, which are performed on mobile phones, has also led to the creation of 'SMS language'.
[src:unintentional-radiator/cellular-telephone] It also led to the growing popularity of emojis.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] In a synchronous logic circuit, the most common type of digital circuit, the clock signal is applied to all storage devices, flip-flops and latches, and causes them all to change state simultaneously, preventing race conditions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] A clock signal is produced by an electronic oscillator called a clock generator.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The most common clock signal is in the form of a square wave with a 50% duty cycle.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Circuits using the clock signal for synchronization may become active at either the rising edge, falling edge, or, in the case of double data rate, both in the rising and in the falling edges of the clock cycle.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Most integrated circuits (ICs) of sufficient complexity use a clock signal in order to synchronize different parts of the circuit, cycling at a rate slower than the worst-case internal propagation delays.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] In some cases, more than one clock cycle is required to perform a predictable action.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] As ICs become more complex, the problem of supplying accurate and synchronized clocks to all the circuits becomes increasingly difficult.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The preeminent example of such complex chips is the microprocessor, the central component of modern computers, which relies on a clock from a crystal oscillator.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The only exceptions are asynchronous circuits such as asynchronous CPUs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] A clock signal might also be gated, that is, combined with a controlling signal that enables or disables the clock signal for a certain part of a circuit.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] This technique is often used to save power by effectively shutting down portions of a digital circuit when they are not in use, but comes at a cost of increased complexity in timing analysis.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Most modern synchronous circuits use only a "single phase clock" – in other words, all clock signals are (effectively) transmitted on a single wire.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] In synchronous circuits, a "two-phase clock" refers to clock signals distributed on two wires, each with non-overlapping pulses.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Traditionally, one wire is called *phase 1* or *φ1* (phi1), the other wire carries the "phase 2" or "φ2" signal.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Because the two phases are guaranteed non-overlapping, gated latches rather than edge-triggered flip-flops can be used to store state information so long as the inputs to latches on one phase only depend on outputs from latches on the other phase.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Since a gated latch uses only four gates versus six gates for an edge-triggered flip-flop, a two-phase clock can lead to a design with a smaller overall gate count, but usually at some penalty in design difficulty and performance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Metal oxide semiconductor (MOS) ICs typically used dual clock signals (a two-phase clock) in the 1970s.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] These were generated externally for both the Motorola 6800 and Intel 8080 microprocessors.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The next generation of microprocessors incorporated the clock generation on chip.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The 8080 uses a 2 MHz clock but the processing throughput is similar to the 1 MHz 6800.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The 8080 requires more clock cycles to execute a processor instruction.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Due to their dynamic logic, the 6800 has a minimum clock rate of 100 kHz and the 8080 has a minimum clock rate of 500 kHz.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Higher speed versions of both microprocessors were released by 1976.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The 6501 requires an external 2-phase clock generator.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The MOS Technology 6502 uses the same 2-phase logic internally, but also includes a 2-phase clock generator on-chip, so it only needs a single phase clock input, simplifying system design.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Some early integrated circuits use four-phase logic, requiring a four-phase clock input consisting of four separate, non-overlapping clock signals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] This was particularly common among early microprocessors such as the National Semiconductor IMP-16, Texas Instruments TMS9900, and the Western Digital MCP-1600 chipset used in the DEC LSI-11.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Four-phase clocks have only rarely been used in newer CMOS processors such as the DEC WRL MultiTitan microprocessor. and in Intrinsity's Fast14 technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Most modern microprocessors and microcontrollers use a single-phase clock.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Many modern microcomputers use a "clock multiplier" which multiplies a lower frequency external clock to the appropriate clock rate of the microprocessor.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] This allows the CPU to operate at a much higher frequency than the rest of the computer, which affords performance gains in situations where the CPU does not need to wait on an external factor (like memory or input/output).
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The vast majority of digital devices do not require a clock at a fixed, constant frequency.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] As long as the minimum and maximum clock periods are respected, the time between clock edges can vary widely from one edge to the next and back again.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Such digital devices work just as well with a clock generator that dynamically changes its frequency, such as spread-spectrum clock generation, dynamic frequency scaling, etc.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Devices that use static logic do not even have a maximum clock period (or, in other words, minimum clock frequency); such devices can be slowed and paused indefinitely, then resumed at full clock speed at any later time.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Some sensitive mixed-signal circuits, such as precision analog-to-digital converters, use sine waves rather than square waves as their clock signals, because square waves contain high-frequency harmonics that can interfere with the analog circuitry and cause noise.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Such sine wave clocks are often differential signals, because this type of signal has twice the slew rate, and therefore half the timing uncertainty, of a single-ended signal with the same voltage range.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Differential signals radiate less strongly than a single line.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Alternatively, a single line shielded by power and ground lines can be used.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] In CMOS circuits, gate capacitances are charged and discharged continually.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] A capacitor does not dissipate energy, but energy is wasted in the driving transistors.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] In reversible computing, inductors can be used to store this energy and reduce the energy loss, but they tend to be quite large.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Alternatively, using a sine wave clock, CMOS transmission gates and energy-saving techniques, the power requirements can be reduced.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The most effective way to get the clock signal to every part of a chip that needs it, with the lowest skew, is a metal grid.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] In a large microprocessor, the power used to drive the clock signal can be over 30% of the total power used by the entire chip.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The whole structure with the gates at the ends and all amplifiers in between have to be loaded and unloaded every cycle.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] To save energy, clock gating temporarily shuts off part of the tree.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The **clock distribution network** (or **clock tree**, when this network forms a tree such as an H-tree) distributes the clock signal(s) from a common point to all the elements that need it.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Since this function is vital to the operation of a synchronous system, much attention has been given to the characteristics of these clock signals and the electrical networks used in their distribution.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Clock signals are often regarded as simple control signals; however, these signals have some very special characteristics and attributes.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Clock signals are typically loaded with the greatest fanout and operate at the highest speeds of any signal within the synchronous system.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Since the data signals are provided with a temporal reference by the clock signals, the clock waveforms must be particularly clean and sharp.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Furthermore, these clock signals are particularly affected by technology scaling (see Moore's law), in that long global interconnect lines become significantly more resistive as line dimensions are decreased.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] This increased line resistance is one of the primary reasons for the increasing significance of clock distribution on synchronous performance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Finally, the control of any differences and uncertainty in the arrival times of the clock signals can severely limit the maximum performance of the entire system and create race conditions in which an incorrect data signal may latch within a register.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Most synchronous digital systems consist of cascaded banks of sequential registers with combinational logic between each set of registers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The functional requirements of the digital system are satisfied by the logic stages.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Each logic stage introduces delay that affects timing performance, and the timing performance of the digital design can be evaluated relative to the timing requirements by a timing analysis.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Often special considerations must be given in order to meet the timing requirements.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] For example, the global performance and local timing requirements may be satisfied by the careful insertion of pipeline registers into equally spaced time windows to satisfy critical worst-case timing constraints.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] A proper design of the clock distribution network helps ensure that critical timing requirements are satisfied and that no race conditions exist (see also clock skew).
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] The delay components that make up a general synchronous system are composed of three individual subsystems: the memory storage elements, the logic elements, and the clocking circuitry and distribution network.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Novel structures are currently under development to ameliorate these issues and provide effective solutions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/clock-signal] Important areas of research include resonant clocking techniques ("resonant clock mesh"), on-chip optical interconnect, and local synchronization methodologies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:unintentional-radiator/compliance-regulation] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] According to requirements of the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), ATC operations are conducted either in English, or the local language used by the station on the ground.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In practice, the native language for a region is used; however, English must be used upon request.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In 1920, Croydon Airport near London, England, was the first airport in the world to introduce air traffic control.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The 'aerodrome control tower' was a wooden hut 15 feet (5 metres) high with windows on all four sides.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] It was commissioned on 25 February 1920, and provided basic traffic, weather, and location information to pilots.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the United States, air traffic control developed three divisions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The first of several air mail radio stations (AMRS) was created in 1922, after World War I, when the U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Post Office began using techniques developed by the U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Army to direct and track the movements of reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Over time, the AMRS morphed into flight service stations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Today's flight service stations do not issue control instructions, but provide pilots with many other flight related informational services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] They do relay control instructions from ATC in areas where flight service is the only facility with radio or phone coverage.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The first airport traffic control tower, regulating arrivals, departures, and surface movement of aircraft in the US at a specific airport, opened in Cleveland in 1930.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Approach- and departure-control facilities were created after adoption of radar in the 1950s to monitor and control the busy airspace around larger airports.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The first air route traffic control center (ARTCC), which directs the movement of aircraft between departure and destination, was opened in Newark in 1935, followed in 1936 by Chicago and Cleveland.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] After the 1956 Grand Canyon mid-air collision, killing all 128 on board, the FAA was given the air-traffic responsibility in the United States in 1958, and this was followed by other countries.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In 1960, Britain, France, Germany, and the Benelux countries set up Eurocontrol, intending to merge their airspaces.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The first and only attempt to pool controllers between countries is the Maastricht Upper Area Control Centre (MUAC), founded in 1972 by Eurocontrol, and covering Belgium, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and north-western Germany.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In 2001, the European Union (EU) aimed to create a 'Single European Sky', hoping to boost efficiency and gain economies of scale.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the USSR, the first air traffic control service was organized in 1929 on the Moscow - Irkutsk air route; in 1930, control areas were defined along all existing air routes.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The primary method of controlling the immediate airport environment is visual observation from the airport control tower.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The tower is typically a tall, windowed structure, located within the airport grounds.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] A controller must carry out the job using the precise and effective application of rules and procedures; however, they need flexible adjustments according to differing circumstances, often under time pressure.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In a study which compared stress in the general population and among staff working in this kind of system, there was markedly showed more stress level for controllers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This variation can be explained, at least in part, by the characteristics of the job.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Remote and virtual tower (RVT) is a system based on air traffic controllers being located somewhere other than at the local airport tower, and still able to provide air traffic control services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Ground control (sometimes known as *ground movement control*, GMC) is responsible for the airport *movement* areas.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Some busier airports have surface movement radar (SMR).
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Air control (known to pilots as *tower* or *tower control*) is responsible for the active runway surfaces.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Clearance delivery is the position that issues route clearances to aircraft, typically before they commence taxiing.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These clearances contain details of the route that the aircraft is expected to fly after departure.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the field of supply chain management, the concept of a "supply chain control tower" reflects the "end-to-end visibility" provided by an air traffic control tower.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Ashutoch Gupta, writing for Gartner, observes that a supply chain control tower can be established "by combining people, process, data, organization and technology to improve visibility, control and decision making".
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] If there is a flight service specialist monitoring the frequency, the specialist will give pilots advisories about traffic, weather, and surface conditions, and may relay IFR clearances from en route controllers, but do not give clearances.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the United Kingdom, weather and traffic information can be provided by radio stations named Air Ground Communications Services (AGCS).
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These similarly inform pilots who are then responsible for decisions made.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Some examples of MF airports in Canada include Kingston/Norman Rogers Airport and Kuujjuaq Airport.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the U.S., TRACONs are additionally designated by a three-digit alphanumeric code.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] For example, the Chicago TRACON is designated C90.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] An area control center, as opposed to a terminal control center, is a specific type of air traffic control center that primarily controls IFR traffic, or aircraft at high altitude flying by instruments, instead of aircraft that are landing or taking off.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Each area control center is assigned a flight information region, and certain area control centers near the coast are also tasked with monitoring aircraft flying over the ocean.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Area control centers perform similar duties to other types of air traffic control, such as rerouting aircraft to deal with adverse conditions and directing the course of aircraft to ensure separation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In order to extend their surveillance capabilities, some air navigation service providers (e.g., Airservices Australia, the U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Federal Aviation Administration, Nav Canada, etc.) have implemented automatic dependent surveillance – broadcast (ADS-B).
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This newer technology reverses the radar concept.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Instead of radar 'finding' a target by interrogating the transponder, the ADS-B equipped aircraft 'broadcasts' a position report as determined by the navigation equipment on board the aircraft.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] ADS-C is another mode of automatic dependent surveillance, however ADS-C operates in the 'contract' mode, where the aircraft reports a position, automatically or initiated by the pilot, based on a predetermined time interval.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] It is also possible for controllers to request more frequent reports to more quickly establish aircraft position for specific reasons.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] However, since the cost for each report is charged by the ADS service providers to the company operating the aircraft, more frequent reports are not commonly requested, except in emergency situations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] ADS-C is significant, because it can be used where it is not possible to locate the infrastructure for a radar system (e.g., over water).
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Operational display systems are now deployed and accept ADS-C inputs as part of their display.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] A radar archive system (RAS) keeps an electronic record of all radar information, preserving it for a few weeks.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This information can be useful for search and rescue.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] When an aircraft has 'disappeared' from radar screens, a controller can review the last radar returns from the aircraft to determine its likely position.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] For an example, see the crash report in the following citation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Air traffic control errors occur when the separation (either vertical or horizontal) between airborne aircraft falls below the minimum prescribed separation set (for the domestic United States) by the US Federal Aviation Administration.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Separation minimums for terminal control areas (TCAs) around airports are lower than en-route standards.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Errors generally occur during periods following times of intense activity, when controllers tend to relax and overlook the presence of traffic and conditions that lead to loss of minimum separation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] According to the Civil Air Navigation Services Organisation (CANSO), weather significantly impacts global aviation, with more than 70% of air traffic delays being attributed to adverse weather conditions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These disruptions cause widespread delays, rerouting by ATC, and cancellations across continents.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In 2024, Europe experienced a 40% increase in weather-related en-route delays compared to 2023.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] As increasingly adverse weather intensifies the frequency and severity of these events, CANSO urged collaboration and real-time solutions among global aviation stakeholders to mitigate the effects of weather on flight operations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Global ATC infrastructure is a complex network that varies significantly by region, with many countries facing challenges related to outdated technology, staffing shortages, and increasing traffic demand.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] While some regions, like parts of Europe and the U.S., have implemented modernization programs such as SESAR and NextGen, many others, especially in developing nations, still rely on legacy radar systems and voice-based communication, which limit efficiency and safety.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These disparities contribute to delays and reduce the overall resilience of global air traffic management.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] According to the ICAO, coordinating ATC systems and accelerating digitalization is essential for meeting future aviation demands.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Similarly, a 2024 report from the International Air Transport Association (IATA) emphasizes the urgency of investing in scalable, data-driven infrastructure to handle post-pandemic growth and ensure sustainability across the network.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Constrained control capacity and growing traffic lead to flight cancellation and delays.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In America, delays caused by ATC grew by 69% between 2012 and 2017.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] ATC staffing issues were a major factor in congestion.Estimates suggest that more efficient ATC could save 5-10% of aviation fuel by avoiding holding patterns and indirect airways.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Accordingly, the explanation of delays as resulting from ATC restrictions has become a common justification used by airlines to deny compensation claims.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] However, several European courts have determined that this rationale is sometimes applied incorrectly, with airlines attributing delays to ATC although all measures haven't been taken by the air carrier concerned to avoid the delays or cancellations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] A prerequisite to safe air traffic separation is the assignment and use of distinctive call signs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These are permanently allocated by ICAO on request, usually to scheduled flights, and some air forces and other military services for military flights.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] There are written call signs with a two or three letter combination followed by the flight number such as AAL872 or VLG1011.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] As such, they appear on flight plans and ATC radar labels.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] There are also the *audio* or *radio-telephony* call signs used on the radio contact between pilots and air traffic control.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These are not always identical to their written counterparts.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] An example of an audio call sign would be 'Speedbird 832', instead of the written 'BAW832'.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This is used to reduce the chance of confusion between ATC and the aircraft.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] By default, the call sign for any other flight is the registration number (or tail number in US parlance) of the aircraft, such as 'N12345', 'C-GABC', or 'EC-IZD'.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The short *radio-telephony* call signs for these tail numbers is the last three letters using the NATO phonetic alphabet (e.g.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] ABC, spoken *alpha-bravo-charlie* for C-GABC), or the last three numbers (e.g.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the United States, the prefix may be an aircraft type, model, or manufacturer in place of the first registration character, for example, 'N11842' could become 'Cessna 842'.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) has spent over US$3 billion on software, but a fully automated system is still yet to be achieved.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In 2002, the United Kingdom commissioned a new area control center into service at the London Area Control Centre (LACC) at Swanwick in Hampshire, relieving a busy suburban centre at West Drayton in Middlesex, north of London Heathrow Airport.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Software from Lockheed-Martin predominates at the London Area Control Centre.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] However, the centre was initially troubled by software and communications problems causing delays and occasional shutdowns.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In the United States, free flight is a developing air traffic control method that uses no centralised control (e.g. air traffic controllers).
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Instead, parts of airspace are reserved dynamically and automatically in a distributed way using computer communication to ensure the required separation between aircraft.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In Europe, the Single European Sky ATM Research (SESAR) programme plans to develop new methods, technologies, procedures, and systems to accommodate future (2020 and beyond) air traffic needs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In October 2018, European controller unions dismissed setting targets to improve ATC as "a waste of time and effort", as new technology could cut costs for users but threaten their jobs.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In April 2019, the EU called for a 'Digital European Sky', focusing on cutting costs by including a common digitisation standard, and allowing controllers to move to where they are needed instead of merging national ATCs, as it would not solve all problems.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Single air-traffic control services in continent-sized America and China does not alleviate congestion.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Eurocontrol tries to reduce delays by diverting flights to less busy routes: flight paths across Europe were redesigned to accommodate the new airport in Istanbul, which opened in April, but the extra capacity will be absorbed by rising demand for air travel.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Well-paid jobs in western Europe could move east with cheaper labour.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The average Spanish controller earn over €200,000 a year, over seven times the country average salary, more than pilots, and at least ten controllers were paid over €810,000 ($1.1m) a year in 2010.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] French controllers spent a cumulative nine months on strike between 2004 and 2016.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Many countries have also privatised or corporatised their air navigation service providers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] There are several models that can be used for ATC service providers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The first is to have the ATC services be part of a government agency as is currently the case in the United States.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The problem with this model is that funding can be inconsistent, and can disrupt the development and operation of services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Sometimes funding can disappear when lawmakers cannot approve budgets in time.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Both proponents and opponents of privatisation recognise that stable funding is one of the major factors for successful upgrades of ATC infrastructure.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Some of the funding issues include sequestration and politicisation of projects.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Proponents argue that moving ATC services to a private corporation could stabilise funding over the long term which will result in more predictable planning and rollout of new technology as well as training of personnel.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] As of November 2024, The United States had 265 contractor towers that are staffed by private companies but administered by FAA through its FAA Contract Tower Program, which was established in 1982.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] These contract control towers cover 51% of all the Federal air traffic control towers in the U.S.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Another model is to have ATC services provided by a government corporation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This model is used in Germany, where funding is obtained through user fees.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Yet another model is to have a for-profit corporation operate ATC services.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This is the model used in the United Kingdom, but there have been several issues with the system there, including a large-scale failure in December 2014 which caused delays and cancellations and has been attributed to cost-cutting measures put in place by this corporation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] In fact, earlier that year, the corporation owned by the German government won the bid to provide ATC services for Gatwick Airport in the United Kingdom.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The last model, which is often the suggested model for the United States to transition to is to have a non-profit organisation that would handle ATC services as is used in Canada.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The Canadian system is the one most often used as a model by proponents of privatisation.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Air traffic control privatisation has been successful in Canada with the creation of Nav Canada, a private non-profit organisation which has reduced costs, and has allowed new technologies to be deployed faster due to the elimination of much of the bureaucratic red tape.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] This has resulted in shorter flights and less fuel usage.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] It has also resulted in flights being safer due to new technology.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Nav Canada is funded from fees that are collected from the airlines based on the weight of the aircraft and the distance flown.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Air traffic control is operated by national governments with few exceptions: in the European Union, only Italy has private shareholders.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Privatisation does not guarantee lower prices: the profit margin of MUAC was 70% in 2017, as there is no competition, but governments could offer fixed terms concessions.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] The United States airspace is divided into 21 zones (centres), and each zone is divided into sectors.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Also within each zone are portions of airspace, about 50 miles (80 kilometres) in diameter, called TRACON (Terminal Radar Approach Control) airspaces.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] Within each TRACON airspace are a number of airports, each of which has its own airspace with a 5 miles (8.0 kilometres) radius.
[src:unintentional-radiator/control-tower] FAA control tower operators (CTO) / air traffic controllers use FAA Order 7110.65 as the authority for all procedures regarding air traffic.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] In United States regulatory law, an **unintentional radiator** is any device that is designed to use radio frequency electrical signals within itself, or sends radio frequency signals over conducting cabling to other equipment, but is not intended to radiate radio frequency energy.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] An **incidental radiator** is a device that can generate radio frequency electrical energy even though it is not intentionally designed to do so.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Unintentional and incidental radio frequency radiation can interfere with other electronic devices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] In the United States, limits on radiated emissions from unintentional and incidental radiators are established by the Federal Communications Commission.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Similar regulations have been promulgated by other governments.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Reference is usually made in regulations to technical standards established by organizations such as ANSI, IEC and ITU.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] A computer is a typical example of an unintentional radiator.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Radio frequency signals used within the computer circuitry may be unintentionally coupled to the power cord or to an interconnecting cable, which then acts as an antenna.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] A radio receiver will often use an intermediate frequency which is detectable outside the radio—the concept behind at least one audience measurement concept for roadside detection of radio stations which passing motorists are listening to.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Examples of incidental radiators include electric motors, transformers, dimmers, and corona from electrical powerlines.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Radiated emissions from these commonly create interference on AM radio receivers and on television receivers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] In North America, active devices that are characterized as unintentional radiators are governed by Part 15 of the FCC regulations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] In Canada, Innovation, Science and Economic Development considers them as interference-causing Equipment.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Globally, most domestic regulation of unintentional radiators are based on ITU recommendations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Generally, this means the device leaks a signal at some level.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Microprocessor-controlled appliances, anything with a clock signal, and switching voltage regulators all make some kind of noise, at the repetition frequency and at harmonics.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] In most countries, government agencies regulate how much leakage is tolerated.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] This prevents leakage from cable television systems, for example, from interfering with radio communications between aircraft and control towers.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Because it costs money to filter out noise, there is always a balance struck between regulatory compliance and perfect filtering in these devices.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] Microwave ovens or devices with microprocessors may leak within allowable limits but may generate an undesired signal that interferes with a licensed communications device.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] It also generally means that users who intentionally radiate signals (TV stations and cell phone companies) can order the device turned off if it interferes with their licensed operations.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] There is an entire industry based on regulatory compliance: manufacturers shipping a product to a foreign country must comply with each country's limitations on leakage of interfering signals.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] For example, in Germany the TÜV issues regulatory rules for unintentional radiators.
[src:unintentional-radiator/unintentional-radiator] The big cylindrical bumps on the cable to monitors and laptop chargers are ferrite cores which reduce undesired signals.
